Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Harris telephone surveys use a form of random digit dialing. From a random multi-stage cluster sampling design, they obtain a national cross-section of U.S. adults. Interviewers are usually given the first five digits of a series of randomly selected residential telephone numbers that have previously been stratified by geographic locations, including minor civil divisions. The interviewer then adds two randomly generated digits to complete a new seven-digit number;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: I;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: H-8220-32;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Survey used a subsample from a national representative stratified cluster area sample. The household sample was selected using one area stage (370 segments) in 15 large urban areas, and using two area stages (35 ""municipios"" and 628 segments) in 35 smaller urban and rural areas. Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Traditionally, the sample for the NHIS is redesigned every ten years to better measure the changing U.S. population and to meet new survey objectives. The fundamental redesign structure of the 1995-2004 NHIS is similar to that of the 1985-1994 NHIS; however, there were two major changes to the sampling design. First, a state-level stratification increased the number of primary sampling units (PSUs) from 198 to 358. This enhanced the capability of using the NHIS for state estimation and future dual-frame surveys at the state level. Users should note that the NHIS is currently not designed to provide state-level estimates; however, in some cases this can be done, particularly for those states with larger populations. Contact the NCHS Research Data Center for more information. Secondly, both the black and Hispanic populations are now oversampled to allow for more precise estimation of health in these growing minority populations. In the previous design, only black Americans were oversampled."; Civilian, noninstitutionalized population of the 50 states and the District of Columbia.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-010-2000-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: Personal interviews conducted in households.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The estimates of personal income and of per capita personal income incorporate the results of the annual revision to the national income and product accounts (NIPAs). The estimates are first prepared for the Nation, then for the States, and then for the counties. The estimates for the regions are aggregations of the State estimates, and the estimates for the metropolitan areas and BEA
economic areas are aggregations of the county estimates.; In the national and regional economic accounts, persons are defined as individuals, nonprofit institutions serving individuals, private noninsured welfare funds, and private trust funds. The last three are referred to as quasi-individuals. Subnational estimates include residents of the United States residing only in the 50 States and the District of Columbia. National estimates also include Federal civilian and military personnel stationed abroad and residents who are employed by U.S. firms and are on temporary foreign assignment.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 30-REIS-1969-2004-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The State and county estimates of personal income are primarily based on administrative records data and on data from censuses or similar surveys. The data from administrative records may originate either from the recipients of the income or from the source of the income. The data from censuses are mainly collected from the recipients of the income.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Harris telephone surveys use a form of random digit dialing. From a random multi-stage cluster sampling design, they obtain a national cross-section of U.S. adults. Interviewers are usually given the first five digits of a series of randomly selected residential telephone numbers that have previously been stratified by geographic locations, including minor civil divisions. Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The MEPS HC collects data through an overlapping panel design. In this design, data are collected through a preliminary contact followed by a series of five rounds of interviews over a two and a half year period. Two calendar years of medical expenditures and utilization are collected from each household. This series of data collection is launched again each subsequent year on a new sample of household to provide overlapping panels of data. A sample of 10,500 household was drawn for the study.;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: II;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: This survey provides data for a sample of the civilian, non-institutionalized population of the United States. Sometimes a special sampling weight is needed for particular data items.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-010-1987-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The basic purpose of the Health Interview Survey (HIS) is to obtain information about the amount and distribution of illness, its effects in terms of disability and chronic impairments, and the kinds of health services people receive. Household variables in this data collection include type of living quarters, size of family, number of families in household, and geographic region. Person variables include sex, age, race, marital status, veteran status, education, income, industry and occupation codes, and limits on activity. The Condition, Doctor Visit, and Hospital files contain information on each reported condition, two-week doctor visit, or hospitalization (twelve-month recall), respectively.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The NHDS utilizes a stratified, multi-stage probability design. The original sample, drawn in 1965 and followed through 1987, was based on a two-stage sampling plan. A new sample was drawn in 1988, when a three-stage sampling plan was implemented and several data collection and estimation procedures were revised. The redesign of the survey is important, especially for those conducting trend analyses. Because the new surve
y differs from the original one in sample design, data collection, and estimation procedures, some of the differences between NHDS statistics based on the 1965-87 sample and statistics based on the sample drawn in 1988 may be due to the survey redesign rather than actual changes in hospital utilization.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-125-2004-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: "The National Hospital Discharge Survey (NHDS) covers discharges from noninstitutional hospitals, exclusive of Federal, military, and Veterans Administration hospitals, located in the 50 States and the District of Columbia. Only short-stay hospitals (those with an average length of stay for all patients of less than 30 days) or those whose specialty is general (medical or surgical) or children's general are included in the survey. These hospitals must also have six or more beds staffed for patient use. These criteria, used since the survey redesign in 1988, differ slightly from those used under the old design. Prior to 1988, hospitals with an average length of stay of 30 days or more were excluded, regardless of specialty. However, the term ""short-stay"" continues to be used because 98 percent of the hospitals in the NHDS universe fall into this category.";

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: This survey provides data for a sample of the civilian, non-institutionalized population of the United States. It is based on a complex multistage design with oversampling of some targeted subpopulations, particularly for minority populations. Sampling weights have been developed to account for the survey design and to provide an adjustment for survey nonresponse. Sometimes a special sampling weight is needed for particular data items.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-010-1990-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The basic purpose of the National Health Interview Survey (NHIS) is to obtain information about the amount and distribution of illness, its effects in terms of disability and chronic impairments, and the kinds of health services people receive. Household variables in this data collection include type of living quarters, size of family, number of families in household, and geographic region. Person variables include sex, age, race, marital status, veteran status, education, income, industry and occupation codes, and limits on activity. The Condition, Doctor Visit, and Hospital files contain information on each reported health condition, doctor visit within a two-week period, and hospitalization (12-month recall), respectively.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Council on Library Resources funded five organizations to conduct a coordinated study of user and nonuser responses to public online catalogs. A ""public online catalog"" is defined for this study as a library bibliographic database that is directly searchable by library patrons through terminals in library buildings or elsewhere. The study involved two questionnaires: one completed at the terminal by catalog users and the other completed in the library by individuals who had not used the computer catalog. Thirty-one library systems comprising seventeen different online catalog computer systems participated in the survey. Data collection took place in April and May 1982. The production consortium consisted of: J. Matthews and Associates, Inc.; Library of Congress; Online Computer Library Center (OCLC); Research Libraries Group (RLG); and the University of California.;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: II;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The NHES is a system of telephone surveys. Households are selected for the survey using random digit dialing (RDD) methods. Each collection of the NHES begins with a screening of a representative sample of households. The samples have ranged in size from 45,000 to 60,000 households. One of the goals of the NHES is to produce reliable estimates of the characteristics of children's and adults' educational experiences for the total targeted population and for domains defined by race and ethnicity. Estimates by race and ethnicity are of great interest, especially for monitoring educational trends over time. Therefore, the NHES sample design over-samples minorities in order to increase the reliability of estimates for these groups. Data are collected using computer-assisted telephone interviewing (CATI) procedures.; Noninstitutionalized civilian population of the United States;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 31-NHES-2001-1-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: Telephone interviews;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The research design includes a survey and comparison of three distinct populations: the elite military, the elite civilian public, and the mass civilian public. The sampling design consists of 24 individual subsamples, with data collection spanning several months and encompassing several modes of administration including a mail questionnaire and telephone interviews. The timing and complexity of the surveys was dictated by the special needs and requirements of the different military institutions as well as the challenge of reaching an elite sample of civilians. The telephone survey of the civilian public, conducted by Princeton Survey Research Associates, includes a subset of questions asked of the elite samples. The survey instrument was designed to generate data that would be comparable to data obtained by earlier surveys of attitudes about foreign and domestic policy.; "(1) Elite mil
itary: officers whose promise for advancement has been recognized by assignment to attend the professional military education course appropriate for their rank; (2) Civilian elite: subsamples were chosen to receive the survey on the basis of their presence in a variety of published directories including Who's Who in America, and other directories of prominent Americans including Clergy, Women, American Politics, State Department, Media, Foreign Affairs, and Labor; (3) Civilian public: a nationally representative sample of adults, 18 and older living in telephone households in the continental United States.";Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: II;Type: ODUM:NOTES.FUNDING Notes: Smith-Richardson Foundation;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The estimates of personal income and of per capita personal income incorporate the results of the annual revision to the national income and product accounts (NIPAs). The estimates are first prepared for the Nation, then for the States, and then for the counties. The estimates for the regions are aggregations of the State estimates, and the est
imates for the metropolitan areas and BEA economic areas are aggregations of the county estimates.; In the national and regional economic accounts, persons are defined as individuals, nonprofit institutions serving individuals, private noninsured welfare funds, and private trust funds. The last three are referred to as quasi-individuals. Subnational estimates include residents of the United States residing only in the 50 States and the District of Columbia. National estimates also include Federal civilian and military personnel stationed abroad and residents who are employed by U.S. firms and are on temporary foreign assignment.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 30-REIS-1969-2008-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The State and county estimates of personal income are primarily based on administrative records data and on data from censuses or similar surveys. The data from administrative records may originate either from the recipients of the income or from the source of the income. The data from censuses are mainly collected from the recipients of the income.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The 2004 NHAMCS is a multi-stage probability probability sample survey of emergency department and outpatient department visits to non-federal, short-stay, and general hospitals in the United States. The NHAMCS was designed to provide estimates based on the following priority of survey objectives: United States; region; emergency and outpatient departments; and type of ownership. The NHAMCS used a four-stage probability design with samples of primary sampling units (PSUs), hospitals within PSUs, clinics/emergency service areas within outpatient/emergency departments, and patient visits within clinics/emergency service areas.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-007-2004-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: Patient visit records from hospital emergency departments and outpatient departments;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Traditionally, the sample for the NHIS is redesigned every ten years to better measure the changing U.S. population and to meet new survey objectives. The fundamental redesign structure of the 1995-2004 NHIS is similar to that of the 1985-1994 NHIS; however, there were two major changes to the sampling design. First, a state-level stratification increased the number of primary sampling units (PSUs) from 198 to 358. This enhanced the capability of using the NHIS for state estimation and future dual-frame surveys at the state level. Users should note that the NHIS is currently not designed to provide state-level estimates; however, in some cases this can be done, particularly for those states with larger populations. Contact the NCHS Research Data Center for more information. Secondly, both the black and Hispanic populations are now oversampled to allow for more precise estimation of health in these growing minority populations. In the previous design, only black Americans were oversampled."; Civilian, noninstitutionalized population of the 50 states and the District of Columbia.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-010-1998-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: Personal interviews conducted in households.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Public Law 94-171, enacted in 1975, requires the Census Bureau to provide redistricting data in a format requested by state governments. Within one year following the decennial census (by April 1, 1991), the Census Bureau must provide the governor and legislature of each state with the population da
ta needed to redraw legislative districts. Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The NIS uses a random-digit-dialing (RDD) telephone survey to identify households containing children in the target age range and interview an adult who is knowledgeable about the child's vaccinations. With the consent of the child's parent or guardian, the NIS also contacts (by mail) the child's health care providers to request information on vaccinations from the child's medical records. Samples of telephone numbers are drawn independently, for each calendar quarter, within 78 Immunization Action Plan (IAP) areas. Of the 78 IAP areas, 28 (including the District of Columbia) are urban areas. The remaining 50 are either an entire state or a rest of state IAP area (where the state contains one or more urban IAP areas). This design makes it possible to produce annualized estimates of vaccination coverage levels within each of the 78 IAP areas. Further, by using the same data collection methodology and survey instruments in all IAP areas, the NIS produces vaccination coverage levels that are comparable among IAP areas and over time.; Children aged 19 to 35 months living in the United States at the time of the interview.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-006-2002-CD;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Each month, a systematic sample of addresses is selected from the most current MAF for the American Community Survey. The sample will represent the entire United States. Each monthly sample will be selected without 'replacing' any addresses used for the American Community Survey in the previous five years. Consequently, no specific address will receive the ACS questionnaire more than once in any five-year period. Larger proportions of addresses will be sampled for small governmental units (American Indian reservations, counties, and townships). The monthly sample size is designed to approxima
te the sampling ratio of Census 2000, including the oversampling of small governmental units.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 14-2-ACS-1996-CD;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: This study used two types of samples. The first is a national cross-section sample using a form of random digit dialing. From a random multi-stage cluster sampling design, they obtained a national cross-section of U.S. adults. Interviewers are usually given the first five digits of a series of randomly selected residential telephone geographic locations including minor civil divisions. The interviewer then adds two randomly generated digits to complete a new seven-digit number. In the second leadership samples, respondents were selected by using systematic probability samples drawn from prepared lists. For more information see accompanying reports.;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: I;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: H-874003;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The Household Survey sample is a stratified multistage area probability design with a total sample of roughly 35,000 individuals in 14,000 households who completed all rounds of data collection. Oversampling of population subgroups of special policy interest includes poor and low-income families, the elderly, the functionally impaired, and Black and Hispanic minorities.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-008-1987-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The National Medical Expenditure Survey (NMES) series provides information on health expenditures by or on behalf of families and individuals, the financing of these expenditures, and each person's use of services. The Household Survey was fielded over four rounds of personal and telephone interviews at four-month intervals. Baseline data on household composition, employment, and insurance characteristics were updated each quarter, and information on all uses of and expenditures for health care services and sources of payment was obtained. In addition to the core data, Public Use Tape 18 provides supplemental information on income, assets, and taxes. Income-related variables distinguish among 26 types of income. Also included are demographic characteristics of respondents (age, race/ethnicity, sex), tax filing status, home ownership, type of occupation, medical deductions, type of payment for health care, day care arrangements for children, pregnancies during 1987, related prenatal care, veteran status, and loss of a close relative or friend.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Harris telephone surveys use a form of random digit dialing. Interviewers are usually given the first five digits of a series of randomly selected residential telephone numbers that have previously been stratified by geographic locations, including minor civil divisions. The interviewer then adds two randomly generated digits to complete a new seven-digit number;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: I;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: H-8221-09;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: This survey provides data for a sample of the civilian, non-institutionalized population of the United States. It is based on a complex multistage design with oversampling of some targeted subpopulations, particularly for minority populations. Sampling weights have been developed to account for the survey design and to provide an adjustment for survey nonresponse. Sometimes a special sampling weight is needed for particular data items.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-010-1991-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The basic purpose of the National Health Interview Survey (NHIS) is to obtain information about the amount and distribution of illness, its effects in terms of disability and chronic impairments, and the kinds of health services people receive. Household variables in this data collection include type of living quarters, size of family, number of families in household, and geographic region. Person variables include sex, age, race, marital status, veteran status, education, income, industry and occupation codes, and limits on activity. The Condition, Doctor Visit, and Hospital Record files contain information on each reported health condition, doctor visit within a two-week period, and hospitalization (12-month recall), respectively.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The estimates of personal income and of per capita personal income incorporate the results of the annual revision to the national income and product accounts (NIPAs). The estimates for the regions are aggregations of the State estimates, and the estimates for the metropolitan areas and BEA economic areas are aggregations of the county estimates.; In the national and regional economic accounts, person
s are defined as individuals, nonprofit institutions serving individuals, private noninsured welfare funds, and private trust funds. The last three are referred to as quasi-individuals. Subnational estimates include residents of the United States residing only in the 50 States and the District of Columbia. National estimates also include Federal civilian and military personnel stationed abroad and residents who are employed by U.S. firms and are on temporary foreign assignment.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 30-REIS-1969-2003-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The State and county estimates of personal income are primarily based on administrative records data and on data from censuses or similar surveys. Important note about source of payment for childbirth. Due to the abundance of options for health insurance coverage in California in 2016, Listening to Mothers in California Survey investigators were unsure whether survey participants with Medi-Cal (Californias Medicaid program) coverage, including many Medicaid managed care plans, would consistently be aware of Medi-Cal as the source of payment for their birth. Investigators thus arranged for the Department of Health Care Services (DHCS) to identify survey participants with a 2016 Medi-Cal-paid childbirth claim in the DHCS Management Information System/Decision Support System (MIS/DSS) Warehouse. All initial survey data analyses (at www.nationalpartnership.org/LTMCA) and all secondary analyses by the investigator team use this gold standard identifier for participants who had Medi-Cal coverage for childbirth. The investigators went to great effort to be able to include this identifier in the public dataset, and received no response from DHCS. The Dataverse dataset therefore does not include this identifier. It does include participants self-reports of source of payment for their childbirth, and the Kappa score of agreement between Medi-Cal-paid claim in MIS/DSS Warehouse and the womens self-reports is 0.81. Thus, there may be some discrepancies between analyses carried out by investigators and by users of the public dataset using the source of payment variable.

The investigators also have access to selected items from participants birth certificates, and are prohibited from including any birth-certificate-derived items in the public dataset.

For the supplementary materials, verification was performed solely for the successful execution of code. All of the manuscript's substantive results replicate successfully. Some minor discrepancies may appear when users attempt to replicate precisely some estimates. This is caused by variations in the computing environment affecting the script's underlying random number generation. Odum replicators have confirmed that discrepancies caused by this do not alter the empirical findings of the manuscript. The verification process was carried out by the Odum Institute for Research in Social Science at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The NHDS utilizes a stratified, multi-stage probability design. The original sample, drawn in 1965 and followed through 1987, was based on a two-stage sampling plan. A new sample was drawn in 1988, when a three-stage sampling plan was implemented and several data collection and estimation procedures were revised. The redesig
n of the survey is important, especially for those conducting trend analyses. Because the new survey differs from the original one in sample design, data collection, and estimation procedures, some of the differences between NHDS statistics based on the 1965-87 sample and statistics based on the sample drawn in 1988 may be due to the survey redesign rather than actual changes in hospital utilization.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-125-1990-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: "The National Hospital Discharge Survey (NHDS) covers discharges from noninstitutional hospitals, exclusive of Federal, military, and Veterans Administration hospitals, located in the 50 States and the District of Columbia. Only short-stay hospitals (those with an average length of stay for all patients of less than 30 days) or those whose specialty is general (medical or surgical) or children's general are included in the survey. These hospitals must also have six or more beds staffed for patient use. These criteria, used since the survey redesign in 1988, differ slightly from those used under the old design. Prior to 1988, hospitals with an average length of stay of 30 days or more were excluded, regardless of specialty. However, the term ""short-stay"" continues to be used because 98 percent of the hospitals in the NHDS universe fall into this category.";
Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: II;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The NHDS utilizes a stratified, multi-stage probability design. The original sample, drawn in 1965 and followed through 1987, was based on a two-stage sampling plan. A new sample was drawn in 1988, when a three-stage sampling plan was implemented and several data collection and estimation procedures were revised. The redesign of the survey is important, especially for those conducting trend analyses. Because the new survey differs from the original one in sample design, data collection, and estimation procedures, some of the differences between NHDS statistics based on the 1965-87 sample and statistics based on the sample drawn in 1988 may be due to the survey redesign rather than actual changes in hospital u
tilization.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-125-2002-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: "The National Hospital Discharge Survey (NHDS) covers discharges from noninstitutional hospitals, exclusive of Federal, military, and Veterans Administration hospitals, located in the 50 States and the District of Columbia. Only short-stay hospitals (those with an average length of stay for all patients of less than 30 days) or those whose specialty is general (medical or surgical) or children's general are included in the survey. These hospitals must also have six or more beds staffed for patient use. These criteria, used since the survey redesign in 1988, differ slightly from those used under the old design. Prior to 1988, hospitals with an average length of stay of 30 days or more were excluded, regardless of specialty. However, the term ""short-stay"" continues to be used because 98 percent of the hospitals in the NHDS universe fall into this category.";

In late 2017, a group of state, local, tribal, regional, and federal air planning agencies initiated a collaborative process to build a national emissions modeling platform (EMP) for simulating air quality in the U.S. The 2016v1 EMP is the latest product from the National Emissions Inventory Collaborative that includes a full suite of base year (2016) and future year inventories, ancillary emissions data, and scripts and software for preparing the emissions for air quality modeling after the 2016 alpha and 2016 beta development in early 2019.
A coordination workgroup, ten sector workgroups, and a modeling workgroup were staffed by over 245 state and regional air agency, EPA, and Federal Land Manager employees. The work of the sector workgroups to build 2016 base year and future year inventories are documented in a series of sector-specific specification sheets below. These specification sheets detail the origin of the inventories and ancillary data used to simulate criteria pollutants, and in many cases hazardous air pollutants, emissions for the U.S., Canada, and Mexico.

The EPA 2016v1 FTP site provides 2016v1, 2023v1, and 2028v1 inventories, smoke inputs and scripts, and summary reports:  ftp://newftp.epa.gov/Air/emismod/2016/v1/

The National Emissions Inventory (NEI) Collaborative Wiki v1 Release Page ( http://views.cira.colostate.edu/wiki/wiki/10202)
: provides links to download the entire modeling platform, specification sheets that describe the data sources and methods used in each sector, and additional analysis products.

Household variables in this data collection include type of living quarters, size of family, number of families in household, and geographic region. Person variables include sex, age, race, marital status, veteran status, education, income, industry and occupation codes, and limits on activity. The Condition, Doctor Visit, and Hospital files contain information on each reported condition, two-week doctor visit, or hospitalization (12-month recall), respectively.;

In late 2017, a group of state, local, tribal, regional, and federal air planning agencies initiated a collaborative process to build a national emissions modeling platform (EMP) for simulating air quality in the U.S. The 2016v1 EMP is the latest product from the National Emissions Inventory Collaborative that includes a full suite of base year (2016) and future year inventories, ancillary emissions data, and scripts and software for preparing the emissions for air quality modeling after the 2016 alpha and 2016 beta development in early 2019.
A coordination workgroup, ten sector workgroups, and a modeling workgroup were staffed by over 245 state and regional air agency, EPA, and Federal Land Manager employees. The work of the sector workgroups to build 2016 base year and future year inventories are documented in a series of sector-specific specification sheets below. These specification sheets detail the origin of the inventories and ancillary data used to simulate criteria pollutants and in many cases hazardous air pollutants, emissions for the U.S., Canada, and Mexico.

List of all measures administered in the study:

In-Lab Self-report Questionnaires
Individual Measures
1. Demographics
2. Relationship information (status, length)
3. Personality
4. Life satisfaction
5. Positive and negative affect
6. Self-regulation
7. Sleep quality
8. Physical symptoms
9. Emotion regulation
10. Self-esteem
11. Perceived stress scale
12. Health conditions
Exercise-Related Measures
13. Exercise behavior over past 2-3 weeks
a. Old questions + IPAQ
14. Exercise intentions over next 2-3 weeks
a. Old questions + IPAQ
15. Partners exercise and intentions over the past 3 weeks
16. Partners exercise intentions and plans over next 3 weeks
17. Exercise approach-avoidance goals (Partner: only if exerciser)
18. Exercise intrinsic motivation (Partner: only if exerciser)
19. Exercise extrinsic motivation (Partner: only if exerciser)
20. Spouse support and control for exercise
a. Partners support of own exercise
b. Own support of partners exercise
c. Overall satisfaction with partners support of own exercise
21. Partners fitness level in comparison to self
22. Exercise goals (strivings assessment) (Partner: only if exerciser)
23. Exercise goals for the relationship partner
a. Own goals for my partners exercise
b. Partners goals for my own exercise
c. Overall: do you think your partner wants to exercise?
24. Action planning (Partner: only if exerciser)
25. Coping planning (Partner: only if exerciser)
26. Exercise self-efficacy
27. Exercise maintenance self-efficacy (Partner: only if exerciser)
28. Exercise relapse self-efficacy (Partner: only if exerciser)
29. Anticipated affective reactions to exercise (Partner: only if exerciser)
30. Exercise motivation (EMI) (Partner: only if exerciser)
31. Barriers to exercise (Partner: only if exerciser)
32. Relationship-specific exercise optimism (Partner: only if exerciser)
Relationship Measures
33. Goal congruence
34. Managing emotions of others
35. Companionship
36. Conflict
37. Relative power
38. Other provides/ participant seeks secure base
39. Pressure
40. Dominance
41. Relationship good/bad
42. Reward/threat
43. Investment model (satisfaction & commitment)
44. Intimacy and achievement motivation
45. Responsiveness (6-item scale)
46. Beliefs about mutual & individualistic caring
47. Closeness (IOS)
48. Centrality of the relationship
49. Attachment style
50. Trust (3-item subscale)

In-Lab Measures (Non-Self-Report)
1. Cognitive tasks
a. Task switching
b. Inhibition
c. Working memory
d. Exercise IAT
e. Relationships IAT
2. Dyadic interaction task (5 minutes each)
a. Discussing own exercise goals
b. Discussing partners exercise (if exerciser) or other goal

Daily Diary End of Day Questionnaire
1. Daily experiences
a. Relationship quality
b. Stress
c. Goals
2. Daily positive and negative emotions
3. Daily exercise plans
a. Actor
b. Partner
4. Exercise activity/experience
5. Reasons for not exercising
6. Exercising together: partner-comparisons
7. Feelings about partner-comparisons
8. Goals for daily exercise
9. Partner support for exercise
10. Own support for partner exercise
11. Satisfaction with partners support for exercise
12. Exercise positive and negative emotions
13. Daily physical symptoms
14. Sleep quality last night
15. Daily self-regulation
16. Relationship quality
17. Failed exercise plans: causal attributions
a. Failure to exercise due to partner
b. Partners degree of control over failure to exercise
18. Feelings about failed exercise
19. Daily problem solving/approach
20. Exercise plans for tomorrow
a. Old items + IPAQ
21. Closeness to partner
22. Subjective cognitive performance items

Experience Sampling Questions
1. Current alertness
2. Current overall mood
3. Current stress
4. Presence of others
5. Current activity
6. Emotional suppression
7. Self-regulating focus/concentration
8. Thought valence
9. Present moment/ mind wandering
10. Stressful events since last signal
11. Satisfaction with romantic relationship
12. Partner responsiveness
13. Goal conflict with partner goals
14. Goal progress
15. Symbol search (used to assess processing speed)
16. Dot memory (used to assess spatial working memory)
17. Flanker task (used to assess inhibition)

Other Daily Measures During the Day
Cortisol samples (3x per day: awakening, 30min post-awakening, end of day)
Activity measure (ActiGraphs)

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The NHDS utilizes a stratified, multi-stage probability design. The original sample, drawn in 1965 and followed through 1987, was based on a two-stage sampling plan. A new sample was drawn in 1988, when a three-stage sampling plan was implemented and several data collection and estimation procedures were revised. The redesign of the survey is important, especially for those conducting trend analyses. Because the new surve
y differs from the original one in sample design, data collection, and estimation procedures, some of the differences between NHDS statistics based on the 1965-87 sample and statistics based on the sample drawn in 1988 may be due to the survey redesign rather than actual changes in hospital utilization.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-125-2994-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: "The National Hospital Discharge Survey (NHDS) covers discharges from noninstitutional hospitals, exclusive of Federal, military, and Veterans Administration hospitals, located in the 50 States and the District of Columbia. Only short-stay hospitals (those with an average length of stay for all patients of less than 30 days) or those whose specialty is general (medical or surgical) or children's general are included in the survey. These hospitals must also have six or more beds staffed for patient use. These criteria, used since the survey redesign in 1988, differ slightly from those used under the old design. Prior to 1988, hospitals with an average length of stay of 30 days or more were excluded, regardless of specialty. However, the term ""short-stay"" continues to be used because 98 percent of the hospitals in the NHDS universe fall into this category.";

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: This survey provides data for a sample of the civilian, non-institutionalized population of the United States. It is based on a complex multistage design with oversampling of some targeted subpopulations, particularly for minority populations. Sampling weights have been developed to account for the survey design and to provide an adjustment for survey nonresponse. Sometimes a special sampling weight is needed for particular data items.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-010-1989-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The basic purpose of the National Health Interview Survey (NHIS) is to obtain information about the amount and distribution of illness, its effects in terms of disability and chronic impairments, and the kinds of health services people receive. Household variables in this data collection include type of living quarters, size of family, number of families in household, and geographic region. Person variables include sex, age, race, marital status, veteran status, education, income, industry and occupation codes, and limits on activity. The Condition, Doctor Visit, and Hospital files contain information on each reported health condition, doctor visit within two- week period, and hospitalization (12-month recall), respectively.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: There are currently 31 separate surveys in 16 countries. In each country, surveys were conducted with a cross-section of between 300 and 1,250 people aged 16 and above, and a separate sample of 50 leaders. The same questionnaire, translated in
to local languages, was used for each country and for both the public and leader samples. Sampling methodology varied from country to country and is described in greater detail in the accompanying report entitled: Public and Leadership Attitudes to the Environment in Four Continents. In most developed countries, the public sample was designed to be representative of all persons aged 16 and over. In most developing countries, the sample was limited to major metropolitan areas and urban centers, because of the impracticality of surveying rural populations. In some countries, the sample was drawn from electoral registers; in others, area probability samples were used. Other countries used ""random walk"" techniques or quota samples. The method employed was generally the one most widely used for surveys of public opinion in that country. In Saudi Arabia, the sample was limited to men. The leadership samples were drawn from a designated list of elected and appointed officials, civil servants, news media, business, religious, trade union, and medical leaders. The number of interviews obtained within each category depended upon the relative importance of each group in the particular country.;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: I;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: H-884002;

Some minor discrepancies may appear when users attempt to replicate precisely the estimates from Table 4. This is caused by variations in the computing environment affecting the script's underlying random number generation. Authors have described the computing environment within which their original results were estimated, and Odum replicators have confirmed that discrepancies caused by this do not alter the empirical findings of the manuscript. The verification process was carried out by the Odum Institute for Research in Social Science at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The estimates of personal income and of per capita personal income incorporate the results of the annual revision to the national income and product accounts (NIPAs). The estimates are first prepared for the Nation, then for the States, and then for the counties. The estimates for the regions are aggregations of the State estimates, and the estimates for the metropolitan areas and BEA economic areas are aggregations of the county estimates.; In the national and regional economic accounts, person
s are defined as individuals, nonprofit institutions serving individuals, private noninsured welfare funds, and private trust funds. The last three are referred to as quasi-individuals. Subnational estimates include residents of the United States residing only in the 50 States and the District of Columbia. National estimates also include Federal civilian and military personnel stationed abroad and residents who are employed by U.S. firms and are on temporary foreign assignment.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 30-REIS-1969-2007-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The State and county estimates of personal income are primarily based on administrative records data and on data from censuses or similar surveys. The data from administrative records may originate either from the recipients of the income or from the source of the income. The data from censuses are mainly collected from the recipients of the income.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Each month, a systematic sample of addresses is selected from the most current MAF for the American Community Survey. The sample will represent the entire United States. Each monthly sample will be selected without 'replacing' any addresses used for the American Community Survey in the previous five years. Consequently, no specific address will receive the ACS questionnaire more than once in any five-year period. Larger proportions of addresses will be sampled for small governmental units (American Indian reservations, counties, and townships). The monthly sample size is designed to approximate the sampling ratio of Census 2000, including the oversampling of small governmental units.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 14-2-ACS-1998-CD;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: This survey provides data for a sample of the civilian, non-institutionalized population of the United States. It is based on a complex multistage design with oversampling of some targeted subpopulations, particularly for minority populations. Sampling weights have been developed to account for the survey design and to provide an adjustment for survey nonresponse. Sometimes a special sampling weight is needed for particular data items.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-010-1993-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: The purpose of the National Health Interview Survey (NHIS) is to obtain information about the amount and the distribution of illness, its effects in terms of disability and chronic impairments, and the kinds of health services people receive. Household Record variables in this data collection include type of living quarters, size of family, number of families in the household, and geographic location. Person Record variables include sex, age, race, marital status, veteran status, education, income, industry and occupation codes, and limitations on activity. The Condition Record file contains information for each reported health condition, with specifics on injury and accident reports. The Doctor Visit Record file documents doctor visits within the time period and identifies acute or chronic conditions. The Hospital Episode Record file contains all recalled accounts of hospitalizations in the 12-month period.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Public Law 94-171, enacted in 1975, requires the Census Bureau to provide redistricting data in a format requested by state governments. Within one year following the decennial census (by April 1, 1991), the Census Bureau must provide the governor and legislature of each state with the population data needed to redraw legislative districts. To meet this requireme
nt, the Census Bureau established a voluntary program to allow states to receive data for voting districts (e.g. election precincts, city wards) in addition to standard census geographic areas such as counties, cities, census tracts, and blocks.; The universe includes all persons and housing units in the United States;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: I;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The NHIS uses a stratified multistage probability design. The sample for the NHIS is redesigned every decade using population data from the most recent decennial census. A redesigned sample was implemented in 1995. This new design includes a greater number of primary sampling units (PSUs) (from 198 in 1994 to 358), and a more complicated nonresponse adjustment based on household screening and oversampling of Black and Hispanic persons, for more reliable estimates of these groups.; Civilian, noninstitutionalized population of the 50 states and the District of Columbia.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 47-010-1997-CD;Type: ODUM:SOURCE.OF.DATA Notes: Personal interviews conducted in households.;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: The data are presented as a world sample of 123 countries. Nations with a population of less than 1 million inhabitants in 1967 are excluded. Data for centrally planned economies are often missing or not comparable. Either these countries do not provide any data or the sources from which the data were derived (as for example, the World Bank) did not include these countries.;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: I;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Stratified multi-cluster sample design. The National Crime Surveys used two samples: national and central city. SSDL holdings contain only the national.;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: 24-008;

Subject: Study Level Error Note, Notes: Harris telephone surveys use a form of random digit dialing. From a random multi-stage cluster sampling design, they obtain a national cross-section of U.S. adults. Interviewers are usually given the first five digits of a series of randomly selected residential telephone numbers that have previously been stratified by geographic locations, including minor civil divisions. The interviewer then adds two randomly generated digits to complete a new seven-digit number;Type: ODUM:ACCESS.CATEGORY Notes: I;Type: ODUM:CODEBOOK.NUMBER Notes: H-8322-09;
